<HL> Plastic Money Takes On a New Meaning As Australia Introduces a 3-D Currency </HL>
<AUTHOR> S. Karene Witcher (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST </CO>
<IN> MON </IN>
<DATELINE> SYDNEY, Australia  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Australian inventors have their way, the world's currencies will never be the same. 

   Their prototype of future money is a revolutionary plastic bank note that sports a three-dimensional hologram. 
Holograms have been used on credit cards for several years to foil forgers. 
But Australian monetary authorities believe they are the first to incorporate such a device on a bank note. 
They hope it will put counterfeiters out of business. 

   The first batch of the new bills, in denominations of 10 Australian dollars ($7.17), came out in late January as part of Australia's bicentennial celebrations. 
The matte finish makes the notes feel like conventional paper money, but they don't fold as easily. 
Plans call for the plastic money to replace all 10-dollar notes this year. 

   Providing the new notes stand the initial test of public handling, Australia intends within three years to replace all its currency with the plastic-hologram notes. 
Like most countries, Australian notes are currently printed on cotton-fiber paper. 

   Moreover, the Reserve Bank, Australia's central bank, hopes to benefit by selling the technology to other countries that print their own money and to companies that print legal tender. 
"We're talking multimillion-dollar export potential," says Bob Pearson, deputy general manager of the Reserve Bank's note-printing branch. 

   Some bank-note printers are skeptical of plastic notes because previous experiments have foundered. 
Du Pont Co. of the U.S. tried to tap the bank-note market in the early 1980s with Tyvek, a plastic used in surgical gowns and other products. 

   Haiti, Costa Rica and the Isle of Man issued Tyvek notes, but a Du Pont official says Haiti and Costa Rica withdrew most of them because the ink tended to rub off. 
The notes fared better on the less-humid Isle of Man, he says. 
Consequently, Du Pont has "temporarily withdrawn" from the bank-note market, says Richard Ludwig, a Du Pont product-development manager in Wilmington, Del. 

   The U.S. considered, and rejected, the use of holograms, primarily because of cost, says a spokesman for the U.S. Treasury's Bureau of Engraving and Printing in Washington. 
"Also, holograms wouldn't necessarily stand the rigors of circulation," he says, adding that the holograms tend to lose their special qualities when the bills are creased. 

   While the Reserve Bank's Mr. Pearson and others won't divulge much about their own technology, they say they have mastered the printing problem by employing, among other things, a modified ink. 
But they have had other headaches. 
Publicity about the note's indestructibility provoked some people to try to prove the inventors wrong and triggered a new round of laboratory testing, Reserve Bank officials say. 

   The 10-dollar note depicts an aborigine on one side and a montage of the settlement of Australia on the other. 
An upper corner bears the holographic image, stamped on a clear-plastic background, of Capt. James Cook, the British explorer who claimed much of the east coast of Australia for Britain in 1770. 

   Unlike in a typical hologram, his image is visible on both sides of the note. 
Different angles produce rainbow patterns, and developers say such an image is harder to counterfeit than a conventional hologram. 

   The clear plastic background of Capt. Cook's portrait also is designed to thwart counterfeiters who use the latest laser-scanner photocopiers. 
The clear plastic areas come out black on photocopies. 

   Holders of about two or three dozen of the initial run of 350,000 10-dollar notes complained to the Reserve Bank that the Cook portrait vanished. 
But examination of the allegedly faulty notes showed evidence of "vigorous rubbing" and "willful damage," a Reserve Bank spokesman says. 
One complainer turned in a note that he said had shriveled when left in the sun on a car dashboard. 
The bank did its own dashboard test and proved it couldn't have happened. 
They suspect the man laid the note on a hot radiator. 

   It is against Australian law to deliberately deface bank notes, but authorities aren't taking action against anyone who presents a damaged note, even if they suspect foul play. 
They don't want to scare away legitimate complaints that might help overcome real flaws. 

   Meanwhile, developers have come up with coatings for the hologram that they hope will stop even the most determined defacers from "taking the smile off Capt. Cook's face," Mr. Pearson says. 
The plastic-based notes, he contends, will stand up to "normal wear and tear." 
They cost slightly more than conventional notes to make but should last 10% to 20% longer. 

   For now, the new 10-dollar notes are in short supply. 
An industrial dispute at the bank's printing facility in Victoria halted production after the initial runs. 
The dispute is resolved, and more notes should be in circulation by the end of the month. 

   Mr. Pearson hopes the next run of notes will be treated less like a curiosity to be scratched and mutilated, and more "for what it is, a damn good bank note." 

</TEXT>
