<HL>
   Du Pont, in Cost-Cutting Move, to Trim
   Thousands of Jobs, Take Big Write-Off
   ----
   By Scott McMurray
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   DD
</CO>
<MS>
BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)
</MS>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<RE>
DELAWARE (DE)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Du Pont Co., seeking to boost profits at its sluggish core
businesses, plans to cut at least $1 billion in fixed costs,
including several thousand jobs, by the end of next year.
   The cost-cutting will require a fourth-quarter charge of
about $350 million, or 50 cents a share, said Edgar S.
Woolard Jr., Du Pont chairman and chief executive officer. In
last year's fourth quarter, Wilmington, Del., Du Pont
reported net income of $468 million, or 69 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Woolard wouldn't disclose the number of jobs that will
be eliminated in the company's chemical, fiber and plastic
businesses, saying only that "there will be a substantial
reduction in the number of our employees" through early
retirement and dismissals. Mr. Woolard said he doesn't
anticipate any plant closings or asset sales as part of the
cost-reduction plan.
   Weakness at Du Pont's major U.S. customers, including the
auto, textile, rubber and computer industries, has depressed
results at Du Pont's chemical and specialty-products units.
Du Pont isn't the only chemical company whose results have
been hurt.
   Investors applauded the cost-cutting move, which analysts
say should widen Du Pont's profit margins as the economy
starts recovering later this year or next year. Du Pont's
stock was quoted at $48.125, up $1.375, in heavy New York
Stock Exchange trading yesterday.
   Securities analysts estimated that at least 10,000 jobs
will be cut, many of them at the company's Wilmington
headquarters. Du Pont has about 143,000 employees world-wide,
including about 26,000 in Delaware. The company's Conoco
petroleum division, which went through a stiff cost-cutting
process in the late 1980s, when oil prices slumped, is
largely going to escape from the cost-cutting.
   Paul Leming, a securities analyst with Kidder, Peabody &amp;
Co. in New York, said Du Pont is focusing on total cost
savings, not on an employee head count, as the most effective
way to trim its bloated costs. "They're not going to let
managers play games and do things like hire people back as
consultants," Mr. Leming noted.
   The company said that in addition to eliminating jobs
through a combination of early-retirement incentives and
dismissals, it's spurring managers to look at cutting
redundant computer systems, consulting and contracting costs,
and travel and entertainment expenses.
   Analysts estimated that Du Pont could save about $1 a
share annually from the planned cost-cutting. But William
Young, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
Securities Corp. in New York, predicted that the savings
would be closer to 75 cents a share, because a portion is
likely to be passed on to customers in the form of lower
prices.
   Sluggish demand accounted for much of the 21% drop in Du
Pont's second-quarter earnings released earlier in the week,
when Du Pont posted profit of $549 million, or 81 cents a
share, compared with $694 million, or $1.02 a share, a year
earlier.
   Du Pont's U.S. sales of chemicals and specialty products
grew less than 1% a year during the 1980s, and the company's
profit margin dropped from 8% to 7%, Mr. Woolard said. Growth
overseas for Du Pont during the same period was nearly twice
as strong, he added.
   Mr. Woolard said that the productivity of Du Pont's
overseas divisions is higher than in the U.S. in part from
the higher growth rates of the European and Japanese auto and
electronics industries.
   Du Pont isn't the only chemical company suffering from
slack customer demand and overcapacity in certain core
chemical and plastics businesses. Earlier this month,
Monsanto Co., St. Louis, reported a second-quarter charge of
$325 million, or $2.54 a share, to cover restructuring and
cost-cutting expenses.
   Moreover, Quantum Chemical Corp. yesterday reported a
second-quarter loss of $87.1 million, or $3.01 a share,
compared with profit of $7.1 million, or 27 cents a share, a
year earlier. Sales fell slightly to $582.5 million from $586
million. The New York-based company said the loss included
write-offs of $53.4 million, mainly from the closing of an
ethylene cracking unit and shrinking petrochemical profit
margins.
</TEXT>
