<HEAD>Du Pont To End Orlon Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty years after it introduced Orlon to
the world of sweaters, socks and knit outerwear, Du Pont Co.
announced Monday it will stop production of the acrylic fiber as
soon as possible.
   The fiber has been overproduced worldwide and consumers now
prefer cotton and polyester fabrics, said Paul G. Gillease,
director of Du Pont's textile division.
   ``As a result, the business has not been sufficiently profitable
in recent years,'' Gillease said.
   Byron J. McCutchen, the company's Orlon business manager, said
that for the past several years, Orlon sales have been about $200
million annually.
   Du Pont plans to focus production on its Lycra spandex fiber,
used in clothing such as swimming suits and leotards; nylon; and
its Dacron polyester.
   Gillease said those fibers ``present significant growth
opportunities (and) will be more beneficial to the long-term
interests of Du Pont and its customers and will strengthen our
position in the U.S. apparel market.''
   Orlon is produced at Du Pont plants in Camden, S.C., and
Waynesboro, Va. There are about 725 employees divided between the
two plants.
   J.J. Pryor, a company spokeswoman, said Du Pont will try to
absorb the workers into other operations.
   She said about 50 Orlon marketing and business employees are
spread among company headquarters in Wilmington, New York and
Charlotte, N.C.
   McCutchen said the phase-out will not affect the Beaumont,
Texas, plant where acrylonitrile is produced. Acrylonitrile is the
raw material used to make Orlon. McCutchen said the raw material
will be sold to other companies.
