<LP>
   WILMINGTON, Del. -- Du Pont Co. disclosed plans to build a
$100 million chlorofluorocarbon-substitutes facility in
Texas.
   The plant, which will be the world's largest making such
products, represents a vote of confidence by the chemical
company in the new product line.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, are widely used as
refrigerants. But growing scientific evidence has suggested
the compounds damage the earth's protective ozone layer. An
international agreement calls for CFCs to be phased out by
the year 2000, and chemical companies have been developing
alternative products to meet that deadline.
   Du Pont introduced its family of CFC substitutes, with the
trade name Suva, earlier this year; the new products have
one-fiftieth or less of the ozone-depleting potential of
Freon, the CFC-based coolant Du Pont makes for a range of
cooling products.
   Du Pont said the plant, which will make the alternative
refrigerants HCFC-124 and HFC-134a, will open in 1993 in
Corpus Christi at the site of a smaller Suva plant. The
company also has a Suva plant currently under construction in
Japan, and a fourth is planned to open in the Netherlands in
1994.
   Earlier this summer, a research consortium of Du Pont and
other chemical makers reported potentially troubling research
results, which showed that lab animals exposed to a CFC
replacement known as HCFC-123 developed nonmalignant tumors.
The Texas plant, however, won't be making that line, which is
aimed at a specialized market for large "chiller" systems.
   Du Pont said its CFC-substitute development expenditures
will total $1 billion by the end of the decade.
</TEXT>
