<TEXT>
   Du Pont Co. third-quarter net income rose 32% as its fibers, chemicals and coal businesses performed better than expected. 

   Net increased to $452 million, or $1.87 a share, from $343 million, or $1.42 a share, in the year-ago period. 
Results included $31 million, or 13 cents a share, from the sale of businesses in 1987, and $21 million, or nine cents a share, from nonrecurring items in 1986. 

   Sales for the quarter grew 19% to $7.59 billion from $6.39 billion a year ago. 

   Richard E. Heckert, chairman, said the strong results show the benefit of steps the Wilmington, Del.-based chemical and energy concern has taken recently to increase productivity. 

   He also said, "The overall demand for the company's products remains strong and we look ahead to the balance of the year with confidence." 

   John J. Quindlen, senior vice president for finance, said Du Pont has "started off the fourth quarter with no reason to believe it won't be as good as we thought." 
He added, however, that it "may be too early to judge if there's any impact" from the stock market's swings. 
If there is, Du Pont won't feel it for about another 30 days, he said. 

   Some analysts who had forecast earnings of between $1.70 to $1.75 a share for the third quarter increased their year-end forecasts. 
Leonard Bogner, an analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities, said he expects Du Pont to earn $7.25 a share for 1987, compared with his early projection of $7.05 a share. 
In 1986, Du Pont earned $6.35 a share. 

   "At least through the end of September, business was going gangbusters," he said. 

   Mr. Bogner said he will watch Du Pont's fourth-quarter results closely for signs of an economic slowdown, which may have been forewarned by last week's stock market crash. 
For example, if retailers cut orders for fibers products, which are sold to the carpet, housing and automobile industries, "we're in for tough economic sledding," he said. 

   But in the third quarter, fibers profit increased 15% to $154 million from $134 million in the year-ago quarter, while sales increased 9% to $1.29 billion from $1.18 billion. 

   Agricultural and industrial chemical profit nearly doubled to $131 million from $68 million in the year-ago period. 
The 1987 figures included a gain of $31 million from the sale of a chlorine and caustic soda production facility. 
Sales grew 19% to $929 million from $783 million a year ago. 

   Profit from the coal business more than doubled to $51 million from $23 million the previous year as sales increased 26% to $456 million from $363 million. 

   Caught in a severe market decline yesterday, Du Pont closed at $81.25 a share, down $6.75, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. 

