<HL>
   Many Big Chemical Concerns Expected
   To Post Sharp 2nd-Quarter Profit Drops
   ----
   By Scott McMurray
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<CO>
   ACY ARC DD DOW LYO MTC RCM UK
</CO>
<MS>
BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)
</MS>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<RE>
CONNECTICUT (CT)
DELAWARE (DE)
MICHIGAN (MI)
MISSOURI (MO)
NEW JERSEY (NJ)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PENNSYLVANIA (PA)
TEXAS (TX)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Many big chemical companies, plagued by an oversupply of
commodity chemicals and plastics and slack demand, are
expected to report sharp earnings declines in the second
quarter.
   While there are indications that demand picked up over the
past several weeks for some companies, industry earnings
aren't expected to improve significantly until sometime next
year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The second quarter didn't show any signs of life, but
we're close to the bottom of the cycle and should start
recovering by year end," says John Roberts, a securities
analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in New York. Chemical
companies speak frequently with Wall Street analysts but
don't comment on earnings projections before the release of
quarterly figures.
   Hardest-hit are the major producers of building block
chemicals and plastics, such as ethylene, styrene and
polyethylene. Strong demand and limited capacity in the late
1980s led to several major commodity plants being built over
the past few years. But the plants recently began adding to
the world's supply of these products just as demand from
developed countries around the world began slowing down.
   Dow Chemical Co. remains the flagship commodity chemical
company in the minds of most investors and analysts, even
though it has been lessening its reliance on the commodity
chemical business for the past decade. Most analysts polled
expect the Midland, Mich., chemical maker to report per-share
earnings of 70 cents to 90 cents a share, compared with $1.34
a year ago.
   "Plunging ethylene and styrene prices are killing Dow,"
says Paul Leming, an analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New
York.
   Dow is fighting back against falling prices, having
announced a four-cent-a-pound increase for certain grades of
polyethylene effective Aug. 1, notes William Young, an
analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. in
New York. But the effort may be a holding action at best, he
says. "They'll be lucky if they can keep the price from
falling further" from current levels of nearly 30 cents a
pound, he adds.
   Union Carbide Corp. has also been hit hard by falling
commodity chemical prices. Analysts expect the Danbury,
Conn., company to report second-quarter per-share earnings of
between 30 cents and 40 cents, compared with 81 cents a year
earlier.
   Du Pont Co., the nation's largest chemical company, relies
much less on commodity chemicals for profits than do Dow and
Union Carbide. But other major business lines at the
Wilmington, Del., company, such as fibers and plastics sales
to the auto and housing industries, have also been suffering.
And quarterly profits from its huge Conoco petroleum
subsidiary also were less than expected, some analysts say.
   Du Pont is expected to report 75 cents to 85 cents a share
for the second quarter, compared with $1.02 a share a year
earlier.
   Operating profit from Du Pont's polymer, or plastics,
division, fell 47% to $70 million in the quarter from $133
million a year ago, estimates Anantha Raman, head of a
research firm bearing his name in Parsippany, N.J. The
company's fibers division sustained a 36% decline in
operating profit, to $100 million from $157 million, and
chemical operating profit plunged 41% to $80 million from
$135 million, Mr. Raman estimates.
   He estimates that the Conoco unit's operating profit from
petroleum products jumped 40% to $232 million from $166
million.
   But Merrill Lynch's Mr. Roberts is less sanguine about
Conoco's performance. This week he cut his second-quarter
estimate for Du Pont to 75 cents a share from 85 cents,
mainly on the belief that refining margins were
"disappointing relative to what people thought they would
be."
   Similar concerns led Mr. Roberts to lower his estimates
for Lyondell Petrochemical Co., Houston, to 75 cents a share
from 85 cents a share, compared with $1.93 a year earlier.
And he cut his second-quarter estimate for Houston-based Arco
Chemical Co. to 40 cents a share from 60 cents a share,
compared with $1.06 a share a year earlier.
   Most analysts had until recently been expecting Monsanto
Co., St. Louis, to report second-quarter per-share profit
fell to $1.65 to $1.80 a share from $1.90 a year earlier.
   But on June 28, Monsanto announced that it was taking a
restructuring charge of $325 million, or $2.54 a share, in an
attempt to make its chemical division more profitable. The
restructuring involves cutting 2,500 employees, or 6% of the
company's 41,000-member work force, and closing several small
plants.
   The fact that Monsanto's stock hardly budged after
announcing the hit to earnings that will leave it with a loss
for the quarter indicates that investors are looking beyond
the latest quarter's results, in expectation of a recovery
beginning by year end or early next year, analysts said.
   American Cyanamid Co. is the healthiest major chemical
company, and may pleasantly surprise Wall Street with
stronger-than-expected second-quarter earnings, predicts Mr.
Roberts. The Wayne, N.J., company is evolving into a medical
concern, with less of its business relying on chemical
products monitored and well understood by chemical analysts,
he said. The company's agricultural chemical business is also
rebounding well compared with last year, and it recently has
been buying back its own stock.
   Analysts estimate American Cyanamid will report
second-quarter profit of $1.30 to $1.40 a share, compared
with $1.16 a share a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

