<HEAD>Du Pont Agrees To Build $1 Billion Complex In Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Du Pont and the Spanish government are to
invest $1 billion over the next 12 years to build a high-tech
industrial complex in the northern region of Asturias under an
agreement signed Thursday.
   Industry Minister Claudio Aranzadi said Spain agreed to put up
$300 million, not counting an undisclosed sum by the Asturian
regional government, to win the complex, which is to employ 1,000
people in the hard-pressed region by 2001.
   Du Pont Chairman Edgar S. Woolard, Jr. said the complex, to be
inaugurated in 1993 with a $200 billion Nomex fiber plant, would
produce a range of chemicals, fibers and polymer products for the
fast-growing European market.
   ``We will bring some of our highest-technology, most specialized
products into this site with the objective of supplying the entire
European market,'' said Woolard, who signed the agreement with
Aranzadi.
   He said the project would further Du Pont's goal of doubling its
annual $5 billion European sales of chemicals, plastics and fibers
over the next decade.
   Both Aranzadi and Woolard said they expected the eventual
investment to exceed the agreed-upon $1 billion and added the
presence of Du Pont would act as a magnet for small- and mid-sized
companies making finished products.
   Even without the additional companies, Du Pont Iberica Chairman
German Lastra said, the complex could be expected to indirectly
create an additional 4,000 to 5,000 jobs in the area.
   The site of the complex is in the Tamon Valley, 6 kilometers
(3.7 miles) from the city of Aviles, which is near the Atlantic
Ocean.
   Woolard said it would be at least six months before the company
would decide on the product to follow Nomex, an aramid fiber used
in aerospace and protective clothing now made exclusively at a Du
Pont plant in Richmond, Virginia.
   But he said the company's commitment to the overall project was
firm.
   ``Du Pont would not be opening this site if there were any
possibility that we were going to build Nomex and stop. It would
not be of interest to us,'' Woolard said.
   Construction on the Nomex plant is to begin in August, with
production expected to start at the start of 1993, Woolard said.
The plant is to employ 300 people.
   Du Pont Iberica now concentrates mostly on marketing in Spain
and Portugal, where it employs 300 people and had sales last year
of $200 million, the company said.
   In Europe, Du Pont employs 20,000 people in 14 countries, and
registered $11 billion in sales last year, company officials said.
</TEXT>
