<TEXT>
   Du Pont Co., as part of an expansion plan, said it will increase its annual capacity for sodium cyanide more than 50%, or 100 million pounds, by mid-1989. 
Terms of the investment weren't disclosed. 

   Under the program, Wilmington, Del.-based Du Pont will build in Texas City, Texas, a plant with capacity of 60 million pounds a year; construction is expected to begin by June. 
The chemical and energy concern said that it will own and market the product world-wide, and that closely held Sterling Chemicals Inc., Houston, will operate the facility, with initial production targeted for the middle of next year. 

   Sodium cyanide is a leaching agent for precious-metals mining. 
The compound also is used in electroplating and in making drugs, vitamins and insecticides. 

   Du Pont said the expansion program also includes a 35-million-pound capacity increase for sodium cyanide over the next six months at its Memphis, Tenn., plant. 
Du Pont also is building a plant in Mexico, with a capacity of 20 million pounds annually, expected to start up in 1989. 

</TEXT>
