<LP>
   MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. -- Allied-Signal Inc. charged Du
Pont Co. with "illegally monopolizing" the $80 million U.S.
market for materials used in military and civilian
bullet-resistant vests.
   Allied-Signal, in a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court
in Newark, N.J., said that Du Pont unlawfully restrained it
from competing with Du Pont's Kevlar synthetic fiber. It also
accused Du Pont of false advertising, which it said
disparaged Allied-Signal's Spectra fiber and Spectra Shield.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company said that until it introduced Spectra, Du
Pont's Kevlar fiber was virtually the only fiber used in
police and military vests. Allied says it currently has about
3% of the market.
   In response, Du Pont said Allied-Signal's suit was
"without merit" and that it will "vigorously" contest the
suit. Du Pont is based in Wilmington, Del.
</TEXT>
