<LP>
   WILMINGTON, Del. -- Du Pont Co., hit like its competitors
with sluggish markets and excess industry capacity, said
second-quarter earnings dropped 21%, despite a slim increase
in sales.
   But the nation's largest chemical company also said its
big fibers operation is seeing what may be the first
glimmerings of a rebounding economy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Net income fell to $549 million, or 81 cents a share, from
$694 million, or $1.02 a share, a year earlier. The earnings
downturn, which was in line with analysts' expectations, came
on sales that increased 1.9% to $9.83 billion from $9.65
billion.
   Du Pont's petroleum operations, acquired when the company
acquired Conoco a decade ago, turned in a sharply higher
performance, with operating profit climbing 38% to $229
million on sales that rose 12% to $3.72 billion. The company
