   Technology:
   Du Pont Unveils Coolants to Substitute
   For CFCs; GM Plans Use in 1994 Cars
   ----
   By Amal Kumar Naj
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
01/22/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   DD ICI GM
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Du Pont Co. introduced a family of
refrigerator and air conditioner coolants as substitutes for
ozone-depleting chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs.
   In one of the first major uses of the substitutes, General
Motors Corp. said it will switch to one of the air
conditioner coolants in cars starting with the 1994
model-year. GM's agreement to use the CFC substitute gives
considerable boost to a line of products whose practical use
had been in serious doubts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Wilmington, Del., chemical company introduced the CFC
substitutes under the trade name "Suva" at a news conference
here. CFCs have been known by Du Pont's trade name "Freon,"
introduced in 1931. But in recent years, scientists have
gathered evidence suggesting that CFCs may be destroying the
ozone layer that shields the earth from the sun's harmful
ultraviolet rays.
   The commercial introduction of the new products will help
Du Pont phase out its CFC production by the year 2000 under
an international agreement known as the Montreal Protocol. Du
Pont executives said the company so far has invested $240
million in 10 facilities in operation, or under construction,
to manufacture the substitutes. Total investment through this
decade is likely to be about $1 billion. Du Pont accounted
for a quarter of the worldwide CFC sale of 1.9 billion pounds
in 1989.
   But the CFC alternatives won't be cheap. The Suva product
aimed at replacing CFC-12, also known as Freon-12, which is
used as a coolant in automobile air conditioners, will sell
for $10 a pound. CFC-12 currently sells for $2.40 a pound,
which includes $1.37 in a special tax instituted by Congress.
   Du Pont officials said the price of Suva, however, will be
cheaper than CFC-12 by 1995. That's because the tax imposed
on CFCs will rise under a scale, and the cost of
manufacturing the alternative will decrease as sales volume
rises.
   Cost aside, the new coolant must overcome other problems.
Use of the product, also called HFC-134a, in automobile air
conditioners will require an all-new lubricant to be mixed
with the refrigerant. But no lubricant has yet been found to
be quite compatible with the 134a, according to a GM
spokesman, who also said the new coolant is slightly less
efficient.
   Nevertheless, GM has committed itself to using the
product. "We are confident that we'll solve the problems,"
the GM spokesman said.
   To accommodate 134a, GM must develop a larger evaporator
and condenser and redesign the compressor on its air
conditioners. Although the GM spokesman declined to say how
much all this would add to the cost of the new car, or what
the auto maker's total retooling costs would be, Du Pont
officials estimated that GM will have to spend up to $1
billion over the next two to three years to convert to the
new coolant.
   Du Pont's products would compete with similar products
introduced last year under the trade name "Klea" by Britain's
Imperial Chemical Industries PLC. A spokesman for ICI's U.S.
unit said the British concern is working with various
automobile manufacturers in the U.S., but doesn't yet have a
firm sales agreement.
</TEXT>
