<HL> Teflon Is 50 Years Old, but Du Pont Is Still Finding New Uses for Invention </HL>
<AUTHOR> Laurie Hays (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> DD </CO>
<IN> CHM </IN>
<TEXT>
   Teflon is already just about everywhere. 

   But 50 years after inventing the nonstick coating, Du Pont Co. doesn't plan to get stuck with a mature product that has only average sales and profits. 
So the push is on to make Teflon even more omnipresent. 

   Du Pont's search for new products is accelerating and advertising budgets and sales forces are being strengthened. 
The goal is to double sales growth to a 10% to 12% annual rate. 
On the industrial side, Du Pont is directly tailoring ideas to customer needs, seeking a greater share of the world's market and looking for ways to reduce production costs. 
On the consumer side, Du Pont wants to increase awareness of Teflon. 

   This spring, for example, the Wilmington, Del.-based chemicals giant will introduce Teflon in a spray can. 
The company envisions coating neckties with it to repel food stains and spraying walls and light switches to protect against dirty fingers. 
The spray was recently exhibited at a ski show as a way to keep clothes dry despite falls in the snow. 
It's already being marketed by General Motors Corp.'s Mr. Goodwrench parts operation as protection for car upholstery. 

   "This stuff is really a nifty chemical," says John Thackrah, business manager for the performance products division of Du Pont. 
"You need a lot of ideas to keep a 50-year-old invention alive." 
Adds David Sanders, director of Du Pont's fluoropolymers business, "We're average on profitability and trying to do better." 

   Finding new uses for Teflon has been an ongoing corporate goal. 
That's how it got on everything from pots and pans to synthetic joints, athletic gear and buildings. 
Industrial applications are its biggest market, with wiring and cables its single biggest use. 
Du Pont, which has captured more than 50% of the world market for such coatings, has produced 2.4 billion pounds of the stuff, enough to coat one frying pan for every human being in the world. 

   For many years, Du Pont couldn't make enough Teflon. 
Its inert, slippery and superior insulating properties were in high demand. 
Sales grew at rates as high as 25% a year and totaled $300 million in 1987. 
But in recent years, sales growth has slowed to between 6% and 8% a year and profits have been "average," according to Mr. Sanders. 

   Du Pont's new strategy extends even to pots and pans. 
It plans to have manufacturers reintroduce its low-end cookware, Teflon 2, the first version of non-stick cookware Du Pont introduced in 1962. 
Teflon 2 was succeeded in the U.S. eight years ago by superior versions -- SilverStone and SilverStone Supra. 

   The Teflon 2 strategy has two objectives. 
Du Pont intends to recapture some of the low-price market that now goes to Silverstone rivals. 
The company hopes that by offering three price choices, shoppers will be willing to pay a little extra for a Du Pont certified product at any level. 
Also, consumers are apparently self-inspired to upgrade purchases, so Du Pont wants to build loyalty starting at the low-end of the scale. 

   On yet another front, Du Pont is working to dust off and modernize Teflon's 1950s image. 
Now under way is a campaign to sell Teflon-treated fabrics and wallpaper as convenience products. 
The fabrics have been around for years, but have "slipped into low profile" and lost ground to Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing Co.'s better-known Scotchgard treatment, according to Cynthia Gray, a Du Pont publicity specialist. 
Du Pont believes women today care less about having a spotless sofa -- the old promotion line -- and more about carefree living styles, she says. 

   "It used to sound like a detergent or polish, something that came in a bucket rather than something that makes your life easier," she says. 

   Yesterday, Du Pont presented the concept at a New York tea party and it plans for the first time to advertise in consumer decorating magazines like House Beautiful and Metropolitan Home. 

   Teflon-treated wallpapers are a new product that Du Pont pins high hopes on. 
"They're scrubbable," says Ms. Gray. 
"You'd have to shoot them to kill them." 

</TEXT>
