<LP>
   Du Pont Co. is launching a sweeping program to cut costs
and improve operating efficiency in a bid to boost annual
pretax profits about $2 billion in five years.
   This latest streamlining by the country's largest chemical
company is in addition to a plan announced in July to cut
costs by $1 billion by the end of 1992.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last year, the Wilmington, Del., company earned $2.31
billion, or $3.40 a share, on sales of $40.05 billion.
   Du Pont and many other chemical companies are retrenching
to cope with excess supplies that have forced down prices of
their commodity chemicals and plastics. Economic slowdowns
around the world also have hurt demand for many chemicals and
plastics.
   Edgar Woolard Jr., Du Pont chairman and chief executive,
said the latest plan calls for the "continuous improvement of
operations" across the company. Du Pont is focusing on
nuts-and-bolts issues such as increasing capacity
utilization, eliminating duplicative work and reducing staff,
among other steps, he said. "This is old fashioned industrial
engineering, not rocket science," he said.
   What he termed Du Pont's "integrated operations" plan
could yield about $1 billion from increased capacity
utilization at Du Pont's manufacturing plants without making
any new investments in them. An additional nearly $1 billion
could come from improving yields, boosting revenue and
eliminating an undetermined number of jobs, he said.
   Mr. Woolard said the company doesn't have a targeted
number of job cuts for the latest plan, adding that the cuts
would come from many areas and wouldn't be concentrated in Du
Pont's white-collar ranks. Du Pont has about 140,000
employees world-wide.
   Mr. Woolard said company planners project that in about
five years the plan could "improve pre-tax earnings in the $2
billion range."
   Investors responded favorably to the news. Du Pont shares
were quoted at $45.625 each, up 62.5 cents, in late New York
Stock Exchange trading yesterday.
   Harvey Stober, an analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
said he raised his rating on Du Pont to "accumulate" from
"hold" based on news of the latest plan. He estimated that
the projected increase in pretax profit translated into about
$2 a share in earnings for Du Pont.
   Mr. Woolard said the plan is being directed by Robert
Luft, senior vice president in Du Pont's chemicals business.
It already has been tried out within a few polymer divisions,
one in chemicals and one in Du Pont's electronics business,
he said.
   Portions of the latest plan were reported in yesterday's
News Journal in Wilmington, where many Du Pont employees read
about it for the first time.
   Mr. Woolard emphasized that the longrange program is
distinct from the plan Du Pont announced earlier this summer
to cut $1 billion in costs by the end of next year. As part
of that plan, Du Pont so far has identified about 5,000 job
cuts.
</TEXT>
