<HEAD>Synar Raps Du Pont Co. Plan To Pay Severance to Weapons Plant
Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman said Tuesday he
would investigate Du Pont Co.'s plan to use $75 million in federal
funds to pay severance benefits to 6,500 workers at a nuclear
weapons plant, even though virtually all will keep their jobs under
new management.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., said ``there is no logical or
equitable reason for the taxpayers to provide a $75 million
windfall to workers who will not lose their jobs or benefits,
solely to enhance Du Pont's corporate image.''
   Synar charged that the Department of Energy, which owns the
Savannah River Nuclear Plant in Aiken, S.C., has failed to actively
resist Du Pont's plan to invoke cost-reimbursable language in its
contract to pay severance to its employees when the company
withdraws from the facility in October 1989.
   He said he had instructed his staff to investigate the matter.
   Du Pont designed and constructed the plant, and since 1950
operated it under government contract before deciding last year to
pull out when the currect pact expires. Under DOE rules, the new
contractor, yet unnamed, must offer jobs and comparable benefits to
all Du Pont employees except for those in 37 key positions or among
support staff at the company's Wilmington, Del., headquarters.
   Synar, chairman of the House Government Operations subcommittee
on the environment, energy and natural resources, said,
``Department of Energy officials appear to be more concerned about
protecting the corporate interests of private contractors than the
government or taxpayers.''
   An Energy Department spokesman, Will Callicott, declined comment
except to say ``it's an issue still under review.'' That review was
triggered in April by the DOE's own inspector general, after it
appeared initially that the department would accept the Du Pont
plan.
   Synar, in a letter to Energy Secretry John S. Herrington, said,
``This delay and inaction only casts doubt on DOE's willingness to
be aggressive in its stewardship of public funds.''
   Synar asked DOE to provide ``all internal analyses, memos, legal
opinions, communications, responses and any other documents
generated by DOE or contractor staff or officials related to the
severance pay issue.''
   Earlier, a Du Pont spokesman, Jim Felder, declined comment on
the case except to note that ``Our employment plans call for the
payment of severance, and we expect the federal government to
reimburse Du Pont for the cost of severance.''
   Under the plan, Du Pont employees would receive a week's pay for
each year of service with the company up until Sept. 30, 1985. That
was the year when Du Pont and DOE agreed to stop accrual of
severance benefits for employees who actually would keep their jobs
under new management.
   Synar said there has been no instance in which the government
paid severance to workers who retained their jobs when there was a
change of contractors at other federal nuclear facilities.
</TEXT>
