<LP>
   WILMINGTON, Del. -- Du Pont Co. said its
agricultural-products unit licensed to Bio-Rad Laboratories
Inc. the exclusive rights to a genetic-particle delivery
system it calls Biolistics.
   The process involves propulsion of microscopic DNA-coated
particles directly into plant and animal cells. The genetic
material introduced via the so-called "gene gun" combines
with existing DNA and can impart new traits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Du Pont said applications of the process include possible
production of disease-resistant or insect-resistant crops, or
higher-yielding plants, as well as potential biomedical
applications.
   The gene gun was developed in the late 1980s by Cornell
University scientists, who formed a closely held company,
Biolistics Inc.; Du Pont acquired rights to the technology in
1989.
   The system uses microscopic pellets of titanium, to which
tiny dabs of genetic material have been attached. The
gene-delivery system then fires millions of such particles
into plant or animal tissue. Du Pont said the system "has
been used successfully to introduce genes into corn,
soybeans, mammalian tissues and microorganisms."
   Bio-Rad, based in Hercules, Calif., makes research
products, diagnostic kits and anlaytical instruments. Under
the pact with Du Pont, it has the right to make instruments
for, "and sell consumables resulting from," the delivery
system.
